I can hardly wait for the outcome of President Trump's Impeachment trial. Reason number 1, (never mind reasons 2 and up) and foremost, it was torture for me and thousands of viewers to watch Mr Schiff standing in front of the microphone, (pardon my sarong for this expression) looking constipated trying to convince the American people and the whole world how bad our president is. Hours and hours of his reading from a notebook and showing clips of what he called proofs of the president's corrupt actions, etc. etc., is enough to make my head spin counter clock wise. While It took only over 2 hours for President Trump's Defense Team to present their simple answer to all the issues that Mr. Schiff had presented as proof of Mr. Trump's so called wrong doings. As a citizen, I love this country, and in my humble opinion, I believe in Mr Trump and trust that he can make this country great again, if we let him do his job. The Democrats are so troubled that they are no longer in control. The Democrats want Mr. Trump's name out before the election, which to my humble opinion again, indicates that they know that Mr. Trump will be voted once again by the same people who believed and trusted Mr. Trump last election.


Most of all, I believe and trust in the wisdom and fairness of our Judicial System to hand down the right decision to this very important event in the history of our country. So help me God,

From India 🙃 >333💓Republic Day honours the date on which the Constitution of India came into effect on 26 January 1950 replacing the Government of India Act (1935) as the governing document of India.[1]

Republic Day￼

The original text of the Preamble to the Constitution of India. The Constitution of India came into force on 26 January 1950.

Observed by￼ IndiaTypeNationalSignificanceInception of Constitution of IndiaCelebrationsParades, distribution of sweets in schools, speeches and cultural dancesDate26 JanuaryFrequencyAnnual

The Constitution was adopted by the Indian Constituent Assembly on 26 November 1949, and came into effect on 26 January 1950 with a democratic government system, completing the country's transition towards becoming an independent republic. 26 January was chosen as the Republic day because it was on this day in 1929 when Declaration of Indian Independence (Purna Swaraj) was proclaimed by the Indian National Congress as opposed to the Dominion status offered by the British Regime.
